The output result is what I expect. Now the lower IR turns into this:
```
realize B([0, 12]) {
  produce B {
    for (ax0, 0, 12) {
      // attr [compute(B.rf, 0x1204368)] realize_scope = ""
      realize B.rf([0, 4], [ax0, 1]) {
        produce B.rf {
          for (k.inner, 0, 4) {
            B.rf(k.inner, (0 + ax0)) =0.000000f
            for (k.outer, 0, 16) {
              B.rf(k.inner, (0 + ax0)) =(B.rf(k.inner, (0 + ax0)) + A((0 + ax0), (k.inner + (k.outer*4))))
            }
          }
        }
        B(ax0) =0.000000f
        for (k.inner.v, 0, 4) {
          B(ax0) =(B(ax0) + B.rf(k.inner.v, ax0))
        }
      }
    }
  }
}
```
I tried to tensorize the k.inner and the k.outer.v, it failed. 
The reason is that rfactor move the rfactor_axis to first dimension, and the shape of new tensor B.rf is [rfactor, axo]. Tensorize with intrinsic shape [rfactor] would not success.
The shape of B.rf cause similar problem for the tensorize of k.outer.v
I think there are two solution:
1. allow using rfactor without moving rfactor_axis to first dimension
1. enhance tensorize to match [n, m, 1] -> [n, m]. while currently the tensorize only allow the match [1, n, m]->[n, m] 

Do you have other better suggestions? @tqchen

@nkyle04 You can do it by `rfactor` (see [doc](http://docs.tvmlang.org/tutorials/language/reduction.html#sphx-glr-tutorials-language-reduction-py))

```python
import tvm

N = 128
V = 8

A = tvm.placeholder((N, N), name='A')
k = tvm.reduce_axis((0, N), name='k')
B = tvm.compute((N,), lambda i : tvm.sum(A[i, k], axis=k), name='B')

s = tvm.create_schedule(B.op)
ko, ki = s[B].split(k, V)
BF = s.rfactor(B, ki)
s[BF].compute_at(s[B], s[B].op.axis[0])
s[BF].vectorize(s[BF].op.axis[0])

print(tvm.lower(s, [A, B], simple_mode=True))
```

